SIMPLE: tool
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tool
<hw>Tool</hw> <pr>(t⟦oomac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>tol</ets>,<ets>tool</ets>. AS. <ets>t⟦omac⟧l</ets>; akin to Icel.
<ets>t⟦omac⟧l</ets>, Goth. <ets>taijan</ets> to do, to make,
<ets>taui</ets> deed, work, and perhaps to E. <ets>taw</ets> to dress
leather. ⟦root⟧64.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An instrument such as a
hammer, saw, plane, file, and the like, used in the manual arts, to
facilitate mechanical operations; any instrument used by a craftsman or
laborer at his work; an implement; <as>as, the <ex>tools</ex> of a
joiner, smith, shoe-maker, etc.</as>; also, a cutter, chisel, or other
part of an instrument or machine that dresses work.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A machine for cutting or shaping materials; -- also
called <altname>machine tool</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, any instrument of use or service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That angry fool . . . ⟦br⟧
Whipping her horse, did with his smarting <qex>tool</qex>⟦br⟧
Oft whip her dainty self.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A weapon.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Him that is aghast of every <qex>tool</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A person used as an instrument by another person; --
a word of reproach; <as>as, men of intrigue have their <ex>tools</ex>,
by whose agency they accomplish their purposes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I was not made for a minion or a <qex>tool</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Burks.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tool</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tool
<hw>Tool</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>tooled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>tooling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shape, form, or
finish with a tool.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Elaborately <xex>tooled</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Ld. Lytton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To drive, as a coach.</def> <mark>[Slang,
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tool</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tool
<hw>Tool</hw> <pr>(t⟦oomac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Tool</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, 2.]</ety> <def>To travel in a vehicle;
to ride or drive.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></p>

<p><q>Boys on their bicycles <qex>tooling</qex> along the well-kept
roads.</q> <rj><qau>Illust. American.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tooling</ent>⟦br⟧
